The FAA Veterans Transition Improvement Act will finish the laudable work that was started by the Wounded Warriors Federal Leave Act.
H.R. 5957 will ensure that newly hired disabled veteran FAA employees receive the same disabled leave as personnel at other gov. agencies
In Washington state there are more than 650 veterans who work at the FAA & across the country more than 15,500 veterans work for the FAA.
However, those not covered under Title 5—including FAA employees—are not able to use these leave benefits.
The Wounded Warriors Federal Leave Act will apply to anyone hired on, or after November 5th of this year.
The Wounded Warriors Federal Leave Act provides up to 104 hours of disabled veteran leave during an employee’s first 12 months on the job.
That bill asserts that no one injured in military service should have to choose between earning a paycheck & receiving healthcare.
Last November, after passing the House and Senate by unanimous consent, the Wounded Warriors Federal Leave Act was signed into law.
Mr. Speaker, I rise today in support of H.R. 5957, the Federal Aviation Administration Veteran Transition Improvement Act of 2016.

Read my full op-ed on why we need to raise the minimum wage in today's @BhamHerald: http://t.co/TlukA1ZR5j
It is unacceptable that millions of people are working full time at the minimum wage but still fall under the poverty line.
Working full time at the minimum wage is not enough to keep families out of poverty.
Women, who make up 49 percent of the workforce, account for 56 percent of low-wage earners.
One in 10 low-wage workers are college graduates, double the number from 1979.
In 1979, 27 percent of low-wage workers were teenagers. Today just 12 percent are. The average age of low-wage workers is 35 years old.
